Exploratory Data Analysis In Python - Credit Score¶

Introduction¶

What is Exploratory Data Analysis ?¶

Exploratory Data Analysis or (EDA) is understanding the data sets by summarizing their main characteristics often plotting them visually. This step is very important especially when we arrive at modeling the data in order to apply Machine learning. Plotting in EDA consists of Histograms, Box plot, Scatter plot and many more. It often takes much time to explore the data. Through the process of EDA, we can ask to define the problem statement or definition on our data set which is very important.

How to perform Exploratory Data Analysis ?¶

The answer is it depends on the data set that you are working. There is no one method or common methods in order to perform EDA.

What data are we exploring ?¶

The Credit Score dataset exist in Kaggle and it uses for Machine learning since it has two separated dataset for test and train. The data-set can be downloaded from here.

To give a piece of brief information about the data set this data contains more of 100, 000 rows and 30 columns which contains Interest_Rate, Num_of_Loan, Type_of_Loan, Delay_from_due_dateNum_of_Delayed_Payment Changed_Credit_Limit Num_Credit_Inquiries Credit_Mix Outstanding_Debt, Credit_Score etc,. We will perform EDA on train dataset.

4. Dropping Irrelevant Columns¶

This step is certainly needed in every EDA because sometimes there would be many columns that we never use in such cases dropping is the only solution. In this case, we only keep the most important columns like Customer_ID, Annual_Income, Num_BankAccounts Num_of_Loan, Num_of_Delayed_Payment, Credit_History_Age and Credit_Score. We could work on different columns based on what project we want to implement or what information stakeholders need. However in this project we only want to explore the whole schema of the credit score for 1, 000, 000 rows and we want to get the most important attributes and work on them.

6. Replacing Invalid Values¶

Some values have invalid values in our cell or have extra characters. As we are mainly dealing with numerical data, in this case, we will replace some characters to make invalid data valid and maintain precious data for our analysis. For instance, by skimming through "annual_income", "num_bank_account", and "num_ofloan", we could see some fields have extra "" characters that we are going to remove.

In [14]:
df = df.replace({'Annual_Income': {'_': None, '-': None, ' ': None}}, regex=True)
df = df.replace({'Num_Bank_Accounts': {'_': None, '-': None, ' ': None}}, regex=True)
df = df.replace({'Num_of_Loan': {'_': '', '-': '', ' ': ''}}, regex=True)
df = df.replace({'Num_of_Delayed_Payment': {'_': None, '-': None, ' ': None}}, regex=True)

We could also use: df = df.replace(r'[^\w\s]|_', '', regex=True)¶

8. Detecting Outliers¶

An outlier is a point or set of points that are different from other points. Sometimes they can be very high or very low. It's often a good idea to detect and remove the outliers. Because outliers are one of the primary reasons for resulting in a less accurate model. Hence it's a good idea to remove them. The outlier detection and removing that I am going to perform is called IQR score technique. Often outliers can be seen with visualizations using a box plot. Herein all the plots, you can find some points are outside the box they are none other than outliers. The technique of finding and removing outlier that I am performing in this assignment is taken help of a tutorial from towards data science.

In [23]:
sns.boxplot(x=df['Annual_Income'])
Out[23]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Annual_Income'>
In [24]:

In [25]:
sns.boxplot(x=df['Num_of_Loan'])
Out[25]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Num_of_Loan'>
In [26]:
sns.boxplot(x=df['Num_of_Delayed_Payment'])
Out[26]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Num_of_Delayed_Payment'>
In [27]:
sns.boxplot(x=df['Credit_History_Age'])
Out[27]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Credit_History_Age'>
In [28]:
Q1 = df.quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df.quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
print(IQR)

Annual_Income             53212.58375
Num_Bank_Accounts             3.00000
Num_of_Loan                   4.00000
Num_of_Delayed_Payment        9.00000
Credit_History_Age           13.00000
dtype: float64

Now we are going to remove outliers¶

In [29]:
df.shape
Out[29]:
(75874, 7)
In [30]:
df = df[~((df < (Q1 - 1.5*IQR)) | (df > (Q3 + 1.5*IQR))).any(axis = 1)]
df.shape
Out[30]:
(69103, 7)

As seen above there were around 8,600 rows were outliers. But you cannot completely remove the outliers because even after you use the above technique there maybe 1–2 outlier unremoved but that ok because there were more than 100 outliers. Something is better than nothing.

At the end we could realize that in the dataset almost 30% of data was invalid and outliers.

10. Plot Features -Scatter, and Histogram¶

Histogram¶

Histogram refers to the frequency of occurrence of variables in an interval. In this case, we have 3 types of credits, Good, Standard, Poor we we wnat compare these three categorical data. To do this histogram is one of the trivial solutions which lets us know the total number credit score group population.

In [34]:
sns.countplot(x=df['Credit_Score'])
Out[34]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Credit_Score', ylabel='count'>

We could make the histogram with annual income too, so it gives us good summary of the income related to credit score¶

In [35]:
df.Annual_Income.value_counts().nlargest(10).plot(kind='bar', figsize=(10,5))
plt.title("Annual Income")
plt.ylabel('Number of People in the Category')
plt.xlabel('Income Groups');

We want to make heat map and other plots to better understand the relationship between features. To do that we are going to assign numeric values to credit scroe, thus, we assign 1 for poor, 2 for standard and 3 for good credit score.¶

In [36]:
df['Credit_Score'] = df['Credit_Score'].str.replace('Good', '3', n=-1)
df['Credit_Score'] = df['Credit_Score'].str.replace('Standard', '2', n=-1)
df['Credit_Score'] = df['Credit_Score'].str.replace('Poor', '1', n=-1)
df['Credit_Score'] = df[['Credit_Score']].apply(pd.to_numeric)
